                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size="2" color="#FFF8DC"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <a href="http://pub142.ezboard.com/feqdivabardsofeverquestfrm55.showMessage?topicID=24.topic" target="_blank">http://pub142.ezboard.com/feqdivabardsofeverquestfrm55.showMessage?topicID=24.topic</a><br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"> decided some of my guild needed a bardic education, so I put together a quick document on bard raid roles. I'm sure I left things out, and some will have differing opinions, so any input will be appreciated. <br /><br />Feel free to repost if you think the lesser classes in your guild will benefit.<br /><br />--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br /><br />I've noticed a couple of times there were raids where I thought that bards could have been put to better use. I figured it might be a good idea to post a list of the various roles a bard can accomplish on a raid, and what tools we need to do each task. The intent of this guide is to outline roles for bards in high level, though not necessarily uber guilds. For reference, the guild this was written for currently recruits 63+ and is working on upper Luclin and lower PoP bosses.<br /><br />It is important to note that songs can have a wide range of effectiveness depending on how they are used. Generally a song has a base effectiveness which is amplified by instrument choice, AA, and some items. For example, Elemental Rhythms as its base raises some resists by 45. If I use a storebought drum (with a 1.8 mod), that goes up to 81. Drums of the Beast (2.6 mod) increase that to 117, and Instrument Mastery 3 (additional .6 mod) brings it up to 144. The epic will perform as a storebought instrument, but is notable in that it acts as an instrument for songs using the singing skill. I have a list of common mods at the end of this document.<br /><br />None of these roles will be a dedicated job on a raid. Instead, the bard should be able to slip in and out of these roles as required. The intent in demarcating the roles is to allow multiple bards an easier time in delegating roles by seeing what roles are appropriate to a situation and whose equipment/AA requirements mesh. For example, the Resist and Debuff roles generally depend on a high percussion mod, and can be best served by a single bard using a drum.<br /><br />Mana Bard:<br />A bard can provide mana to his group and to those around him. There are two lines of song that can do this. The first is the standard mana song, and the second is the hp/mana song. Standard mana song provides an amplifiable amount of mana per tick to group members only. It does not persist, and does not have an icon. This means multiple bards in a group can sing this song and stack mana regen. HP/Mana comes in group and AOE form. The HP portion of the song can be amplified by string instruments, but there is no evidence that the mana portion can be amped. This song leaves an icon, and will repeat for 3 ticks. It cannot stack, so only the highest level song will work.<br />Maximum mana would then be a twist of the hp/mana with 2 ticks of pure mana and Amplification. However, this is rarely an effective use, and should be reserved for drawn out battles where multiple bards are present.<br />32: Chorus of Clarity (Singing) - Adds 7*mod mana/tick to group, stacks<br />58: Chorus of Replenishment (String) - Adds 13*mod HP, 14 mana/tick AOE<br />62: Wind of Marr (String) - Adds 20*mod HP, 21 mana/tick to the group<br />64: Chorus of Marr (String) - Adds 20*mod HP, 21 mana/tick AOE<br /><br />Resist Bard<br />The resist bard can raise resists to incredible levels. The standard resist songs on raids are Elemental Chorus and Purifying Chorus. These are both amplified by drums, so a good drum and instrument mastery help here. For single group, there is Psalm of Veeshan, but is generally used for the damage shield and not the resists. If I think my group is in added need of resists, due to importance of the group or lack of healing available, I will use Psalm, but otherwise a Chorus generally suffices.<br />54: Elemental Chorus (Percussion) - raise fire, cold, magic resists aoe by 45 * mod AOE<br />56: Purifying Chorus (Percussion) - raise poison, disease, magic resists aoe by 45 * mod AOE<br />63: Psalm of Veeshan (Singing) - 15*mod DS, 75*mod all resists, 7*mod AC<br /><br />De-buff Bard<br />Some mobs need resistances lowered before the heavy hitter debuffs will land. Our resist debuffs have the advantage of being unresistable, so by opening with them we can give the rest of the debuff team a chance to land slow, cripple, and all the other devastating debuffs they can throw on. In addition, can lower AC/Agi on mobs to allow them to be hit easier, which comes in very handy on those high-AC Luclin encounters. Lastly, dex debuffing can help cut down on the number of flurries and rampages on mobs with that ability. Use caution with debuffs, however, as they are generally high on aggro. While we want our debuffs to be the first in place, we don't want to take aggro from the MT.<br />39: Katta's Song of Sword Dancing (Percussion) - Increase Dex by 40*mod, add a proc that lowers target Dex by 25<br />51: Largo's Absonant Binding (Singing) - Reduce AC by 19*mod, Reduce Agi by 52*mod, reduce attack speed by 35%, reduce movement by 66%<br />55: Occlusion of Sound (Percussion) - Lower target fire, cold, magic resists by 10 * mod<br />65: Harmony of Sound (Percussion) - Lower target fire, cold, magic resists by 15 * mod<br /><br />Mana-Drain Bard<br />Related to the debuffing, but important enough for its own category is mana draining. When fighing most high level caster mobs, it is generally advantageous to allow them to cast, as it often reduces their DPS. However, most caster mobs pulled away from their bind point will attempt to gate when at low health, which generally means they go get all their friends and relatives and come back to wipe the raid. Lost Comp is our way to help cut down on the gaters. The hope is, by the end of the fight, the mob won't have the mana to gate, and the raid won't get trained by a dozen flurry drakes.<br />60: Ervaj's Lost Composition (Brass) - Drain 220*mod mana from target<br /><br />Damage Shield Bard<br />When the raid allows for it (non slowable and/or flurry mob), this is probably the Bard's greatest contribution to a raid. A bard can stack multiple damage shields together to create a seriously punishing damage shield. The bard needs to be in the MT group for this to work, and as one of the songs involved is a major group resist buff, it will also help keep the tank alive.<br />57: McVaxius' Rousing Rondo (Brass) - 23% haste, 22*mod Str, 15*mod ATK, 8*mod DS<br />62: Warsong of Zek (Brass) - 60% haste, 37*mod Str, 18*mod ATK, 15*mod DS<br />63: Psalm of Veeshan (Singing) - 15*mod DS, 75*mod all resists, 7*mod AC<br />30: Amplification - Additional singing mod, up to +1<br /><br />De-Aggro Bard<br />A bard can improve the DPS of a group of wizards by resetting their hate list to 1. This allows the wizzies to avoid overnuking while still laying the smack down. The bard does this by using our group invulnerability song when the wizzies feel like they're about to get aggro. It wipes the hate list, the wizzie clicks it off and resumes nuking. Simple.<br />60: Kazumi's Note of Preservation - Group Invulnerability 18 seconds<br /><br />Puller Bard<br />PoP gave bards 2 very powerful tools. The first is an AA called Fading Memories. This AA lets us wipe ourselves off a hate list, and turns us invisible. Rogues have this too, but the bard advantage is ours can be used as long as we have 900 mana. With enough Flowing Thought and Mental Clarity, the bard can fade fairly often (Because of this, bards should at least be given heavy consideration on any bard usable FT items, as such items are very rare). The second tool is an upgraded lull song which, when coupled with a CHA buff, can let us grab singles in seconds where a monk or SK might spend minutes. Other classes have such spells, but lack the ability to shed aggro on a failure. We also have a song that allows us to send mobs back to their bind point. This too combines with fading memories to grant us a pulling advantage, as we can pull a swarm, poof the undesirables, then fade aggro away from all but the intended target. I admit I haven't played with this as much as I'd like, as I'm on a less than optimal computer at the moment, but it is something that should be explored. Not to replace the FD puller, but to augment it.<br />56: Song of Highsun - Return mob to spawn point<br />61: Silent Song of Quellious - Lull mob<br />63(POP AA, 6 points): Fading Memories - Wipe hate list and invis, 900 mana<br /><br />DPS Increase Bard:<br />Not a full role, but positioning a bard with melees (or nukers at 64) allows them to use Warsong of the Vah Shir or Rizlona's Call of Flame to increase haste over the cap. Call of Flame also increases nuke damage.<br />60: Warsong of the Vah Shir - 25% Haste, ignores cap<br />64: Rizlona's Call of Flame - 35% haste, ignores cap, 20% bonus to nukes<br /><br />Bard Positioning:<br />At least one bard on the raid should be positioned with the two tanks that are most likely to be MT/ST at any time. The rest should be spread out with melee and nukers as required. If mana is scarce, a bard can be grouped with multiple clerics, but due to the relatively small mana advantage this gives, it should be a sign to reconsider the raid at hand (if this matters, you're cutting it too close). The exception to this is drawn out battles where the mana granted over time will add up in the end (See: Luclin).<br /><br />Equipment and AAs:<br />Bards should make an effort to obtain the best drum available to them. Pre-PoP this was the drums of the beast, with a 2.6 mod. The Thunderous Drums of Karana are a rare drop in BoT that give a 2.8, and there is a 3.2 mod drum in the elemental planes. Other instruments are of lesser concern, as few string, wind, or brass instruments have a noticably better effect than the epic. Bards should make an attempt to get primary hand versions of each, if possible, but won't be hampered without. I carry a Verlekarnorm's Horn of Disaster, potentialy to use with damage shields, but have only found one situation where it was preferable to just using a weapon and meleeing.<br /><br />For raiding AAs, Instrument Mastery 3 is the best bet to channel to, though 6 points in FM once the bard is 63 is a good idea. Singing mastery 3 will give a boost to damage shields as well as some resists and debuffs, but isn't called for as often as IM. In general there are a lot of opinions on AA order, and it will be up to the personal preferences of the bard. <br /><br />Mods of Typical Raiding Gear<br />Percussion:<br />Epic: 1.8<br />Walrus Skin Drum: 2.3 (not primary hand)<br />Drums of the Beast: 2.6<br />Thunderous Drums of Karana 2.8<br />IM3: +.6<br /><br />Singing:<br />Epic: 1.8<br />Voice of the Serpent (Ssra Drop): +.6<br />Amplification (song): +1<br />SM3: +.6<br /><br />Brass:<br />Epic: 1.8<br />Horn of Disaster: 2.2<br />IM3: +.6<br /><br />Strings:<br />Epic: 1.8<br />Lute of the Howler 2.2<br />IM3: +.6<br /><br />Wind: There are currently no songs of any import that use wind. I'd still find a good primary wind instrument and keep it in case this changes, you may need it on an indoor CR one day. <hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"></span id="msg"></font></td>
                    </tr>
